    <div id="post">
  <h1 class='post-title'>The IMVU Story (According To Its VP Engineering)</h1>
I was at [James Birchler](http://twitter.com/jamesbirchler)'s talk, hosted by
[Rich Collins](http://twitter.com/richcollins) of the San Francisco [Lean Startup Circle](http://www.meetup.com/Lean-Startup-Circle/).



I've attended Eric Ries' presentation when he was in
[Vancouver](http://www.meetup.com/vancouver-ruby-rails/events/10021600/?eventId=10021600&action=detail).

Lean Startup

[1] I have seen Eric Ries in
[presentation](http://www.meetup.com/vancouver-ruby-rails/events/10021600/?eventId=10021600&action=detail)
when he was in Vancouver. As I remembered, was more polished and
idealistic. IMVU, in his account, is the poster child of Lean.


Vision.
Focus on customer value.

What I thought interesting

lean startup from afar, and the lean startup experience conveyed by James.

I thought James stuck too much to the LeanStartup party line.

how the culture allows radical experiments.
 surprised by how often

incremental improvement VS non-evolutionary leap.
 old IMVU
   ignored customer feedback
   accumulated cruft. each one was an improvement.
 new IMVU
   james didn't go into details to this, but this was the most interesting part for me.
     vision.

James said he's not a particularly good engineer. What he's good at is listening
and communicating. What struck me is that he said it's good to have somebody
just walking around and asking how people are doing. So people know that
somebody cares.  [link to my article happiness begets creativity]

Slides here, from a different event, but the same deck.

http://www.slideshare.net/jamesbirchler/experimenting-your-way-to-success-applying-lean-startup-principles-to-product-development-at-imvu


measure how happy and productive people are. IMVU use subjective & qualitative interviews.

